CSS looks simple on the surface — colors, boxes, flexbox, done. But under that familiar surface sits a huge set of features that even experienced developers never touch. Here’s a tour of CSS capabilities that quietly solve problems people usually reach for JavaScript to fix.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

1. :has() — The Parent Selector
For years, CSS couldn’t select a parent based on its children. Not anymore.
/* Style a card only if it contains an image */
.card:has(img) {
border: 2px solid #333;
}/* Style a form group when its input is invalid */
.form-group:has(input:invalid) {
background: #fee;
}/* Highlight a label when its checkbox is checked */
label:has(input:checked) {
color: green;
}This alone eliminates a huge chunk of JavaScript that exists purely to toggle classes based on child state.
2. Container Queries — Responsive to the Parent, Not the Viewport
Media queries respond to the screen. Container queries respond to the element’s own container — which is what “responsive components” actually needed all along.
.card-container {
container-type: inline-size;
container-name: card;
}
